{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PfnoDmSBjwFhD6Lfw17gbf","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→You are designing a CLI Gemini protocol browser in Rust before implementation.\n     2→\n     3→Read the requirements in prompts/implement.md to understand the full scope.\n     4→\n     5→Your job is to produce a detailed design document at `DESIGN.md` in the project\n     6→root. Do NOT write any Rust code yet. Only produce the design document.\n     7→\n     8→## What the design document must cover\n     9→\n    10→### Module structure\n    11→- List each source file and its purpose\n    12→- Define the public API of each module (struct names, key method signatures)\n    13→- Show how modules depend on each other\n    14→\n    15→### Data types\n    16→- Define the key structs and enums:\n    17→  - Gemini response (status code, meta, body)\n    18→  - Parsed text/gemini line types (enum with variants for each line type)\n    19→  - Navigation state (history stack, current URL, current page links)\n    20→  - Error types\n    21→- Show the enum variants and struct fields explicitly\n    22→\n    23→### Protocol flow\n    24→- Step-by-step description of what happens when the user navigates to a URL:\n    25→  1. URL parsing/resolution\n    26→  2. TLS connection\n    27→  3. Request sending\n    28→  4. Response header parsing\n    29→  5. Body reading\n    30→  6. Content rendering\n    31→  7. Prompt for next command\n    32→\n    33→### Edge cases to handle\n    34→- List the specific error conditions and how each is handled\n    35→- Redirect chains (max hops, loop detection)\n    36→- Malformed responses\n    37→- Connection timeouts\n    38→- Large response bodies (size limit)\n    39→- Preformatted toggle state tracking\n    40→\n    41→### Test strategy\n    42→- What unit tests to write for each module\n    43→- What edge cases each test covers\n    44→- Note: no network-dependent tests\n    45→\n    46→Write the design document clearly enough that a developer could implement the\n    47→full project from it without referring back to the original requirements.\n    48→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01EAKuUouRmJ3a4iBQWLZ1wd","session_id":"87510e8f-028e-4687-9903-d33073502bb8","uuid":"1229f1f3-b681-4efd-8209-a77ff941e56d"}
