{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TPaTyHSWR6EPLZ6qfF3XNV","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→You are building a CLI Gemini protocol browser in Rust. This is a text-mode\n     2→client for the Gemini protocol (gemini://, port 1965, TLS-wrapped).\n     3→\n     4→A design document has been written at `DESIGN.md` in the project root. Read it\n     5→first — it defines the module structure, data types, and architecture you should\n     6→follow. Implement the full project according to that design.\n     7→\n     8→## Requirements\n     9→\n    10→### Core protocol\n    11→1. Connect to Gemini servers over TLS on port 1965\n    12→2. Use rustls for TLS. Accept all server certificates (skip verification) —\n    13→   Gemini's trust model (TOFU) is out of scope for v1\n    14→3. Send requests in the format: `gemini://host/path\\r\\n`\n    15→4. Parse response headers: `<STATUS><SPACE><META>\\r\\n` followed by body\n    16→5. Handle all status code families:\n    17→   - 1x INPUT: prompt the user for input, re-request with query string\n    18→   - 2x SUCCESS: display the body according to the MIME type in META\n    19→   - 3x REDIRECT: follow the redirect URL (limit to 5 hops, detect loops)\n    20→   - 4x TEMPORARY FAILURE: display error, return to prompt\n    21→   - 5x PERMANENT FAILURE: display error, return to prompt\n    22→   - 6x CLIENT CERTIFICATE: display \"client certificates not supported\"\n    23→\n    24→### text/gemini rendering\n    25→6. Parse text/gemini line types:\n    26→   - Text lines (default)\n    27→   - `=>` link lines — display with a numbered index for navigation\n    28→   - `# `, `## `, `### ` heading lines\n    29→   - `* ` unordered list items\n    30→   - `> ` quote lines\n    31→   - Preformatted toggle blocks (``` opens/closes)\n    32→7. Apply ANSI colors to rendered output:\n    33→   - Headings: bold (h1 also gets a color)\n    34→   - Links: cyan with index number\n    35→   - Quotes: dim/italic\n    36→   - Preformatted: displayed as-is, no wrapping\n    37→\n    38→### Interactive navigation\n    39→8. Display a `> ` prompt after rendering a page\n    40→9. Commands:\n    41→   - A number (e.g. `3`) follows link #3 from the current page\n    42→   - `back` or `b` goes to the previous page (maintain a history stack)\n    43→   - `go <url>` navigates to an arbitrary URL\n    44→   - `quit` or `q` exits\n    45→   - `help` or `?` shows available commands\n    46→10. If the user enters a bare URL starting with `gemini://`, navigate to it\n    47→\n    48→### URL handling\n    49→11. Parse and normalize gemini:// URLs\n    50→12. Resolve relative URLs from link lines against the current page URL\n    51→13. Default port is 1965, default path is /\n    52→\n    53→### Project structure\n    54→14. Use these dependencies in Cargo.toml:\n    55→    - `rustls` (latest 0.23.x) for TLS\n    56→    - `webpki-roots` for root certificates\n    57→    - `url` for URL parsing\n    58→    - No async runtime — use std::net::TcpStream with rustls::StreamOwned\n    59→15. Organize into modules:\n    60→    - `main.rs` — entry point, REPL loop\n    61→    - `gemini.rs` — protocol client (connect, request, parse response)\n    62→    - `parser.rs` — text/gemini line parser\n    63→    - `render.rs` — ANSI terminal renderer\n    64→    - `url_utils.rs` — URL parsing and resolution helpers\n    65→16. Write unit tests in each module using `#[cfg(test)]` blocks:\n    66→    - Test response header parsing (all status families)\n    67→    - Test text/gemini line type parsing (all line types, toggle state)\n    68→    - Test URL resolution (relative paths, absolute paths, cross-origin)\n    69→    - Test redirect loop detection\n    70→    - Do NOT write tests that require network access\n    71→\n    72→### Error handling\n    73→17. Use a custom error enum with `thiserror` for all error types\n    74→18. Handle connection timeouts (5 second default)\n    75→19. Handle malformed responses gracefully (don't panic)\n    76→20. Limit response body size to 5MB\n    77→\n    78→## Guidelines\n    79→- Write idiomatic Rust — proper error handling with Result, no unwrap() in\n    80→  non-test code, use iterators and pattern matching\n    81→- The code must compile with zero warnings under `cargo clippy -- -D warnings`\n    82→- Format with `cargo fmt`\n    83→- All tests must pass with `cargo test`\n    84→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01EAKuUouRmJ3a4iBQWLZ1wd","session_id":"87510e8f-028e-4687-9903-d33073502bb8","uuid":"0a24b104-2f91-4623-81ad-e7076c6ae8ed"}
