{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YBxh9AEXcsrVUaHCeVsJXm","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→You are working on a Ruby project. Implement the following change:\n     2→\n     3→## User Request\n     4→(Contents of .cloche/prompt.txt will be injected here by the adapter)\n     5→\n     6→## Guidelines\n     7→- Follow existing project conventions if files already exist\n     8→- Write tests for new functionality\n     9→- Run tests locally before declaring success\n    10→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01PB2FoeV4tsuHgPF56K4Qdh","session_id":"87510e8f-028e-4687-9903-d33073502bb8","uuid":"762644cf-f11e-4105-a5eb-24367c6d1c9a"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TRiPDFQgh3cBqreUmfjWfT","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→You are designing a mini Redis server in C before implementation.\n     2→\n     3→Read the requirements in prompts/implement.md to understand the full scope.\n     4→\n     5→Your job is to produce a detailed design document at `DESIGN.md` in the project\n     6→root. Do NOT write any C code yet. Only produce the design document.\n     7→\n     8→## What the design document must cover\n     9→\n    10→### Architecture\n    11→- Single-threaded event loop using `poll()` (not `select()`, not `epoll()`)\n    12→- How multiple concurrent client connections are managed\n    13→- Request/response lifecycle from socket read to write\n    14→\n    15→### Data structures\n    16→- Hash table for the key-value store (define the hashing strategy, collision\n    17→  handling, and resize policy)\n    18→- How TTL/expiration is tracked and enforced (lazy expiration on access +\n    19→  periodic sweep)\n    20→- String representation (length-prefixed to handle binary data)\n    21→\n    22→### RESP protocol parsing\n    23→- Define the exact wire format for each RESP type:\n    24→  - Simple Strings (+OK\\r\\n)\n    25→  - Errors (-ERR message\\r\\n)\n    26→  - Integers (:42\\r\\n)\n    27→  - Bulk Strings ($5\\r\\nHello\\r\\n and $-1\\r\\n for null)\n    28→  - Arrays (*2\\r\\n$3\\r\\nfoo\\r\\n$3\\r\\nbar\\r\\n)\n    29→- How partial reads are buffered per-connection\n    30→- How pipelined commands are parsed and executed\n    31→\n    32→### Commands to support\n    33→- PING, ECHO\n    34→- GET, SET (with EX seconds option), DEL\n    35→- EXPIRE, TTL\n    36→- KEYS (with glob pattern: *, ?, [abc])\n    37→- EXISTS, TYPE\n    38→- INCR, DECR\n    39→- Command dispatch table design\n    40→\n    41→### Memory management strategy\n    42→- Ownership rules: who allocates, who frees\n    43→- When hash table entries are freed (delete, overwrite, expiration)\n    44→- Connection buffer lifecycle\n    45→- How to avoid double-free and use-after-free\n    46→\n    47→### File layout\n    48→- List each .h and .c file with its purpose\n    49→- Which functions are public (in headers) vs static\n    50→\n    51→### Test strategy\n    52→- Unit tests for: RESP parser, hash table, glob matching, TTL expiration\n    53→- Integration tests for: command execution, pipelining, concurrent clients\n    54→- How to structure the test harness (test runner with assertions)\n    55→- Memory safety testing approach (valgrind)\n    56→- What specific edge cases each test covers\n    57→\n    58→Write the design document clearly enough that a developer could implement the\n    59→full project from it without referring back to the original requirements.\n    60→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01EAKuUouRmJ3a4iBQWLZ1wd","session_id":"87510e8f-028e-4687-9903-d33073502bb8","uuid":"b4a6b6ca-42a2-4e34-a6e2-3b38e42a48b7"}
