{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QQ2vHHtvQZCrdiJRdDhb4Q","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→You are building a mini Redis server in C. This is a single-threaded,\n     2→in-memory key-value store that speaks the RESP (Redis Serialization Protocol)\n     3→wire protocol over TCP.\n     4→\n     5→A design document has been written at `DESIGN.md` in the project root. Read it\n     6→first — it defines the architecture, data structures, and file layout you should\n     7→follow. Implement the full project according to that design.\n     8→\n     9→## Requirements\n    10→\n    11→### Server\n    12→1. Single-threaded event loop using `poll()` for I/O multiplexing\n    13→2. Listen on a configurable port (default 6379)\n    14→3. Accept multiple concurrent client connections\n    15→4. Handle partial reads/writes correctly (buffer per connection)\n    16→5. Support command pipelining (multiple commands in one TCP segment)\n    17→6. Graceful shutdown on SIGINT/SIGTERM\n    18→\n    19→### RESP protocol\n    20→7. Parse all RESP types: Simple Strings, Errors, Integers, Bulk Strings, Arrays\n    21→8. Handle null bulk strings ($-1\\r\\n)\n    22→9. Correctly handle commands split across multiple TCP reads\n    23→10. Correctly handle multiple commands in a single TCP read (pipelining)\n    24→\n    25→### Commands\n    26→11. PING → +PONG\\r\\n (or PING <message> → bulk string echo)\n    27→12. ECHO <message> → bulk string reply\n    28→13. SET key value [EX seconds] → +OK\\r\\n\n    29→14. GET key → bulk string or null bulk string\n    30→15. DEL key [key ...] → integer (count of deleted keys)\n    31→16. EXISTS key [key ...] → integer (count of existing keys)\n    32→17. EXPIRE key seconds → integer (1 if set, 0 if key doesn't exist)\n    33→18. TTL key → integer (-2 if not exists, -1 if no expiry, else seconds)\n    34→19. KEYS pattern → array of matching keys (support *, ?, [abc] globs)\n    35→20. TYPE key → +string\\r\\n (only type is \"string\")\n    36→21. INCR key → integer (error if value is not an integer)\n    37→22. DECR key → integer (error if value is not an integer)\n    38→\n    39→### Data store\n    40→23. Hash table with open addressing (linear probing or Robin Hood)\n    41→24. Automatic resize when load factor exceeds 0.7\n    42→25. Keys and values are binary-safe (length-prefixed, not null-terminated)\n    43→26. Lazy expiration: check TTL on every access\n    44→27. No background expiration sweep needed for v1\n    45→\n    46→### Memory management\n    47→28. Zero memory leaks — every malloc has a corresponding free\n    48→29. No use-after-free, no double-free, no buffer overflows\n    49→30. All strings are length-prefixed (not relying on null terminators for data)\n    50→31. Connection buffers are freed on disconnect\n    51→\n    52→### Build system\n    53→32. Makefile with targets: `all` (builds server), `test` (builds and runs tests),\n    54→    `test_bin` (builds test binary without running), `clean`\n    55→33. Compile with: `gcc -Wall -Wextra -Werror -pedantic -std=c11 -g`\n    56→34. Source files in `src/`, test files in `test/`\n    57→35. Test runner binary: `test_runner`\n    58→\n    59→### Tests\n    60→36. RESP parser tests:\n    61→    - Parse each RESP type correctly\n    62→    - Handle incomplete/partial messages (return \"need more data\")\n    63→    - Handle malformed input\n    64→37. Hash table tests:\n    65→    - Insert, lookup, delete\n    66→    - Overwrite existing key\n    67→    - Resize triggers correctly\n    68→    - Iterator covers all entries\n    69→38. Glob pattern matching tests:\n    70→    - Literal match, * wildcard, ? wildcard, [abc] character class\n    71→    - Edge cases: empty pattern, empty string, consecutive wildcards\n    72→39. TTL/expiration tests:\n    73→    - Set expiry, check before/after expiration\n    74→    - Key access after expiry returns null\n    75→    - DEL removes expiry\n    76→    - Overwrite key resets expiry\n    77→40. Integration tests (connect to server over TCP):\n    78→    - Basic GET/SET round-trip\n    79→    - Command pipelining (send 3 commands, read 3 responses)\n    80→    - INCR on non-existent key (should create with value 1)\n    81→    - INCR on non-integer value (should return error)\n    82→    - SET with EX, wait, GET returns null\n    83→    - KEYS with various glob patterns\n    84→    - Multiple concurrent connections\n    85→41. The test harness should:\n    86→    - Start the server as a child process on a random high port\n    87→    - Connect as a client, run commands, verify responses\n    88→    - Kill the server after tests complete\n    89→    - Print clear pass/fail for each test case\n    90→    - Exit 0 if all pass, non-zero if any fail\n    91→\n    92→## Guidelines\n    93→- Write standard C11. No compiler-specific extensions.\n    94→- No external dependencies — only libc and POSIX APIs.\n    95→- Must compile cleanly with `-Wall -Wextra -Werror -pedantic`\n    96→- Must pass valgrind with zero leaks and zero errors\n    97→- Keep functions short and focused. No function over 80 lines.\n    98→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01EAKuUouRmJ3a4iBQWLZ1wd","session_id":"87510e8f-028e-4687-9903-d33073502bb8","uuid":"b500347d-4b45-45f8-a3b7-ab415868363d"}
